INSERT INTO `journals` VALUES ('53712','27515','Issue','3626','Michel Michel wrote:\r\n> I have a question regarding timezones. Right now the system is used only in The Netherlands. But for example if the system is also used in Canada (with canadian branches and employers), what is the best thing to do?\r\n> \r\n> 1 - Set timezone per user, or based on chosen country in employer settings\r\n> 2 - Or let browser/client-side decide what is the timezone\r\n> \r\n> Only with option 2, it can bring problems when some user in The Netherlands has an english Operating system with not right timezone. It will break planning (we had this issue before)\r\n> \r\n\r\nThis happens because calendar functionality was wrong implemented. System can\'t based on user browser settings.\r\n\r\n> Need some ideas and info here.\r\n> \r\n> Thanks!\r\n\r\n\r\nThe proper way to implement this is to set time zone for each worker and each branch. \r\nThen the whole functionality is to display planning calendar in correct way. \r\nFor example: \r\n- we add branch with time zone \"America/New_York\"\r\n- we add planing for user that is in \"Europe/Amsterdam\", but we plan it with local timezone (\"America/New_York\")\r\n- we log in as administrator who have time zone \"America/New_York\" and we see correct planing\r\n- then worker with time zone set to \"Europe/Amsterdam\" log in and... system recalculate time/date into they time zone and display it correctly for that person. \r\n- everybody see correct planing, everyone for they current localization/timezone.\r\n\r\nSummarizing in properly working system, every object (branch, worker, whole system) have there own time zone, and then system recalculate this times into correct value for current view and loged-in user.','2011-08-26 17:14:10');
