INSERT INTO `journals` VALUES ('54386','22590','Issue','3626','Hashing algorithm and it strength is important but not most important. \r\nWhy somebody will crack hashed password when they already have full access to database?\r\nMore important is to make server (hosting) more safe and user password more difficult. \r\nFirst of all I suggest to set up SSL (https) for erp. Also force users to change passwords to more difficult one (this is already done in other ticket). \r\nAlso I propose to consider cut-off system from internet and make it visible only from selected location (if this possible - static IP addresses needed).\r\n\r\nOther think, that Yuri said below, there is not much possibilities to make problem for somebody who is not \'inside\' system. So, we should make system inaccessible for anonymous users.','2011-08-30 19:06:33');
INSERT INTO `journals` VALUES ('54389','21630','Issue','1561','There is some issue, reported by client:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe following incident happened a few times:\r\n\r\nWhen user is changing their password, system also checks if user has a available valid e-mail adres. If this is not the case, then the password is not changed and the user cannot login. This also happens to user accounts who have an e-mailadres set. The issue then is probably because some characters used in the e-mailadres are marked as \'not valid\'. (for example a.b.c.@hotmail.com is marked as not valid, same for A_B@hotmail.com). \r\n\r\nSo for some users this caused issues, as a workaround we set a not existing e-mail adres to the useraccount. \r\n\r\nBy changing the verification algorithm of the e-mail adres field, it should solve the problem.','2011-08-30 19:12:54');
