INSERT INTO `journals` VALUES ('57778','27959','Issue','1561','Leuconoe S&H wrote:\r\n> Michel Michel wrote:\r\n> > This is reply from client:\r\n> > \r\n> > In theory it\'s possible that a store can have a turnover of \'0\'. Therefore for the specified fields we have to remove the standard value \'0\' so that users should always fill in a value (even if they have to fill in \'0\'). This way we can implement form validation for the specified fields.\r\n> \r\n> We can implement this like you write above, but... That solution is not changing anything! What is the difference between the automatically filled in 0 value and the 0 value filled in by the user? I think that the automatically filled in 0 value is even more user-friendly. Let me know!\r\n\r\nWell for sure it\'s user-friendly. But the thing is, that many users sometimes forget to fill in fields. If those fields have form-validation, and \'0\' values are always parsed standard, they still will forget to fill in these values. So in this case we make it a bit \'less\' userfriendly to be sure users ALWAYS fill in values.','2011-09-13 21:17:22');
